General Charles "Chuck" Yeager, a pioneer and legendary pilot, passed away. He served in the Army Air Corps and the United States Air Force for over 30 years, achieving numerous aerial victories in World War II and commanding Airmen in the wars in Korea and Vietnam. Yeager was known for pushing the boundaries of human achievement and was one of the greatest pilots in history. On October 14, 1947, he became the first person to break the sound barrier while piloting a Bell X-1 jet named "Glamorous Glennis." This achievement, surpassing the Soviet Union, marked a significant milestone in aviation history. General Yeager's life exemplified the spirit of American patriots and proved that there are no limits to human possibility. The article expresses condolences to the Yeager family and highlights the immeasurable influence General Yeager had on the country and the world.